# 🚀 The Ultimate Playwright Cheat Sheet (Review & Q&A)

## 1. Core Concepts (الأساسيات)

* **What is the primary purpose of the `test` function in Playwright?**
    It defines a single test case. It groups your steps together and provides built-in tools (fixtures) like `page` and `browser` to use inside the test.

* **Why is it important to use `await` when calling asynchronous functions?**
    Because JavaScript does not wait for actions to finish by default. `await` forces the code to PAUSE until the action (like clicking or loading) is 100% complete before moving to the next line.

* **What is the purpose of the line `browser.newContext();`?**
    It creates a fresh, isolated browser session (like an Incognito window). It does not share cookies or cache with other tests.

## 2. Navigation & Waiting (التنقل والانتظار)

* **What describes the purpose of `await page.goto(...)`?**
    It navigates the browser to a specific URL (website address).

* **What does `await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');` do?**
    It waits until the network is quiet (no active API calls or loading resources for at least 500ms). This is very useful when a page loads data dynamically after opening.

## 3. Handling Multiple Pages / Tabs (التعامل مع الصفحات المتعددة)

* **How can you identify if a new page has successfully opened after clicking a link?**
    By setting up a "listener" for the new page event using `context.waitForEvent('page')`.

* **What is the purpose of `const [newPage] = await Promise.all([...]);`?**
    It runs multiple actions AT THE SAME TIME (in parallel). 
    - We MUST use it when clicking a link opens a new tab.
    - It starts listening for the new page AND clicks the link simultaneously, so we don't miss the page opening.
    - `[newPage]` extracts the new page object from the result so we can control the new tab.

## 4. Locators & Finding Elements (البحث عن العناصر)

* **CSS Selectors (Space vs. No Space):**
    - `.class1.class2` (No Space): An element that has BOTH classes.
    - `.parent .child` (With Space): A descendant. Looks for `.child` INSIDE `.parent`.

* **What is the purpose of `page.locator(".card-body b").allTextContents()`?**
    It finds ALL bold elements (`<b>`) that are inside elements with the class `.card-body`. Then, `allTextContents()` extracts the text from ALL of them and returns them as a JavaScript Array (e.g., `["Phone", "Laptop"]`).

* **Handling Hidden Inputs (The Checkbox/Radio trick):**
    Developers often hide the real `<input>` and display a custom `<span>` or `<label>`. 
    - **Rule:** Never try to click a hidden `<input>`. Always use Playwright to click the VISIBLE layer (like the `span` or `label`).
    - Example: `await page.locator('.customradio .radiotextsty').click();`

## 5. Actions & Reading Data (التفاعل واستخراج البيانات)

* **Which method is used to fill in the user's email in a form?**
    The `.fill()` method. 
    - Example: `await page.locator('#email').fill('test@test.com');`

* **Reading Text: `textContent()` vs `inputValue()`**
    - `textContent()`: Use this for static UI text (like `<div>`, `<p>`, `<h1>`). It reads the text physically written between the HTML tags.
    - `inputValue()`: Use this for interactive fields (like `<input>`, `<textarea>`). It reads the dynamic value that a user typed into the box.

## 6. Smart Locators (User-Facing Locators)
Instead of complex CSS, use what the user sees:
* `getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' })`: Finds a button with the text "Submit".
* `getByLabel('Username')`: Finds the input field associated with the "Username" label.
* `getByText('Welcome back')`: Finds any element containing this exact text.


